<h3 id="80-prepare-your-model-class-for-migration">8.0 Prepare Your Model Class for Migration</h3>

<p>8.1 Enter this code snippet (below) and hit enter.</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>dotnet ef migrations add initialcreate
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>This will create a snapshot file ready for migration. You can use different filename in the â€œinitialcreateâ€ just avoid spaces and other illegal characters.</p>

<p>After you hit enter, youâ€™ll notice it created a folder with a name of â€œMigrationsâ€ and files with with a name of â€¦_initialcreate.cs and also MyDbContextModelSnapShot.cs</p>

<p><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10904957/34876484-b52527ea-f7dc-11e7-8e64-6a3ea994595d.PNG" /></p>

<p>If you open the â€¦_initialcreate.cs file, youâ€™ll notice this codes.</p>

<p><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10904957/34876540-ffe481cc-f7dc-11e7-913b-b8aac2522e42.PNG" /></p>

<p>Basically, what it saying, â€œHey, Iâ€™m going to CreateTable with a name of â€œStudentsâ€ this table has a columns of Id which is nullable isnâ€™t allowed (false) and IdentityColumn(Primary Key and Auto Increment). Iâ€™m going to create other columns too, the Firstname, Lastname and Section that allows string values.</p>

